, which is a typical feature to enable the bacillus persistence during the long TB latency period (Barry et al. 2009). Mtb has evolved new strategy to escape granulomas leak into the lung and expectorate bacilli (Ehlers and Schaible 2013). The granuloma then serves as a battle ground between mycobacteria and host immune cells. The host-pathogen dynamics decide granuloma to promote or inhibit the infection and then determine the disease outcomes (Ulrichs and Kaufmann 2006; Ehlers and Schaible 2013). An imbalanced interplay between Mtb and immune cells result in the failure of controlling infection, then lead to the LTBI reactivation (O’Garra et al. 2013).

